<HEADLINE>
<P>
CALIFORNIA IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
SACRAMENTO; 
</P>
<P>
LAWMAKER URGES 'A DIAPER CHANGE' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and Wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"California needs a diaper change," state Sen. Lucy Killea (D-San Diego) told 
reporters at Sacramento's Shalom School, which welcomes infants who wear cloth 
diapers. 
</P>
<P>
Killea announced legislation that would require manufacturers of disposable 
diapers to warn consumers that the diapers are contributing to the nation's 
garbage crisis. Saying 26% of the 266 California child-care centers she 
surveyed refuse to accept infants who use cloth diapers, she added that her 
bill also would prohibit "diaper discrimination" at child-care centers. 
"Single-use throwaway diapers represent the most significant consumer item 
entering our landfills today," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
