<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN BRIEF: SCIENCE / MEDICINE; 
</P>
<P>
HERPES RELIEF CLAIMED FOR DRUG 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Compiled from staff and wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A Finnish skin specialist said last week that he and other researchers had 
successfully tested a drug that gave considerable relief to sufferers from both 
strains of herpes. 
</P>
<P>
Allan Lassus said researchers outside Finland found the drug, Genivir, also 
relieved virulent skin rashes in patients with AIDS. 
</P>
<P>
He said he had tested the preparation in the form of a cream on 200 patients 
with genital herpes and 60 with common herpes and found it reduced the length 
of the attacks. 
</P>
<P>
The herpes virus can appear in the form of painful cold sores on the lips, in 
the eyes or on the genitals. There are two strains, both incurable, one of 
which is a sexually transmitted disease commonly known as genital herpes. 
</P>
<P>
"It reduced lip herpes episodes from the usual 10 days to just over five days 
and genital herpes from seven days to 3 1/2 days," Lassus said. The compound 
had an antiviral and immunological effect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
