<P>
MANY PEOPLE NEED HELP: LANDERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SEATTLE 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ann Landers says "a lot of people need professional help," including those who 
write excessively long letters to advice columnists. 
</P>
<P>
The veteran agony aunt said she skimmed through 1,500 letters on a flight 
Friday from Chicago to Seattle where she spoke to the Northwest Women's Show. 
</P>
<P>
Letters on old themes, like those from teen-agers asking how to get more 
attention from a potential mate, can be boring, she admitted. And, naturally, 
she prefers letters that are reasonably concise. 
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes I'll get people who write 14 pages or so, but those people are 
probably psychotic, though," she said. "I tell them they need professional 
help. You know, a lot of people need professional help." 
</P>
<P>
One recurrent theme is whether toilet paper should be hung over the top or down 
against the wall. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm very compulsive about it," she said. "The toilet paper needs to be hung 
down along the wall. I'll actually rearrange it myself if I'm over at someone's 
home and I see it hung over the top." 
</P>
</TEXT>
